Government is confident sufficient safety measures are in place but there are fears that congestion at the Beitbridge border post could lead to a humanitarian crisis. MUSINA - Twenty land borders were reopened on Monday after more than a month of closure to try to curb the spread of COVID-19. Government is confident sufficient safety measures are in place but there are fears that congestion at the Beitbridge border post could lead to a humanitarian crisis. READ: Beitbridge border post truckers unhappy with queues Truck drivers are asking both the South African and Zimbabwean governments to improve infrastructure at the border to avoid congestions and delays. Authorities say adequate measures are in place to deal with the influx of people at the border between the two countries.